2. Open DevTools and set the [CPU throttling](https://developer.chrome.com/docs/devtools/performance/#simulate_a_mobile_cpu) to the lowest value (don't close the DevTools).
3. Refresh the page. You should see the all components in dark mode at first glance.
import { internal_resolveProps as resolveProps } from '@mui/utils';

export default function getThemeProps(params) {
  const { theme, name, props } = params;

  if (
    !theme ||
    !theme.components ||
    !theme.components[name] ||
    !theme.components[name].defaultProps
  ) {
    return props;
  }

  return resolveProps(theme.components[name].defaultProps, props);
}

steps.text:
Yes—this is supported through the public `styled` and `useThemeProps` APIs.

```tsx
import { styled, useThemeProps } from '@mui/material/styles';

const MyCustomComponentRoot = styled('div', {
  name: 'MyCustomComponent',
  slot: 'Root',
})(({ theme }) => ({
  padding: theme.spacing(1),
}));

export function MyCustomComponent(inProps) {
  const props = useThemeProps({
    props: inProps,
    name: 'MyCustomComponent',
  });

  return <MyCustomComponentRoot {...props} />;
}
```

With `name` and `slot`, theme entries at `components.MyCustomComponent` can provide:

- `defaultProps` via `useThemeProps`
- `styleOverrides`
- `variants` via `styled`

For TypeScript, declare the custom component’s theme key using module augmentation (extending `Components`, `ComponentsPropsList`, and, when needed, the overrides/variants maps). This keeps custom components aligned with Material UI’s own theming architecture.
